  <section class="home-section consulting-prose">
    <p>I take consulting work through LW Research and Advisory, LLC.</p>

    <p>The work usually starts when someone has a pile of material – interviews, reports, half-finished drafts, decks, field notes – and a deadline pressing in. The shape of the problem isn't the deliverable. It's the question of what the deliverable should be, and what the material has been saying that no one has yet put into words.</p>

    <p>I'm useful on questions of research ethics, consent, organizational learning, and public engagement in the governance of contested technologies. I work in health, science, and public-interest settings. The substantive vocabulary tends toward strategy, sensemaking, and the kinds of judgment that documents and methods sharpen – and the kinds they quietly replace.</p>

    <p>If you'd like to talk, send me a short note: what you're working on, what feels stuck, what you need by when. I'll read it. If I'm the wrong person, I'll say so, and try to point you to someone who can help.</p>

    <p>If we do talk, the first call is on me. I'd rather not charge before I know I can be useful. The purpose of this call is for me to get a sense of the problem, and for you to feel like you're <a href="https://stephango.com/in-good-hands">in good hands</a>.</p>

    <p>After that, scope and rate are something we work out in writing.</p>
  </section>

